d that the roots of these agreements lie in the promise they hold for improving the welfare of member states. Others have posited that trade agreements are a response to global political conditions. Edward Mansfield and Helen Milner argue that domestic politics provide a crucial impetus to the decision by governments to enter trade pacts. Drawing on this argument, they explain why democracies are more likely to enter PTAs than nondemocratic regimes, and why as the number of veto players--interest groups with the power to block policy change--increases in a prospective member state, the likelihood of the state entering a trade agreement is reduced. The book provides a novel view of the political foundations of trade agreements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommercial treaties. 0aInternational trade. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Trade & Tariffs.2bisacsh  aEuropean Union.  aNorth American Free Trade Agreement.  abalance of power.  adomestic political conditions.  adomestic politics.  aeconomic integration.  aglobal business cycle.  aglobal political economy.  ahegemony.  ainternational relations.  ainternational trade agreements.  ainternational trade.  apolitical economy.  apreferential market access.  apreferential trading arrangements.  aratification.  aregime type.  astrategic interaction.  atrade barriers.  atrade relations.  aveto players.1 aMilner, Helen V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400842537zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400842537423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400842537.jpg  a978-3-11